<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="470" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1213,1814]" box="[151,1273,1213,1238]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,1213,1238]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Host plants.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[301,367,1213,1238]" name="Israel" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Israel</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sternlicht" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[378,549,1213,1237]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ithaburensis">
<emphasis box="[378,549,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Q. ithaburensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[604,711,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<taxonomicName box="[604,707,1213,1237]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="libani">Q. libani</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Elsewhere: 
<emphasis box="[849,1273,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<taxonomicName box="[849,951,1213,1237]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="libani">Q. libani</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lindl" authorityYear="1840" box="[962,1075,1213,1237]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brantii">Q. brantii</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1086,1269,1213,1237]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="castaneifolia">Q. castaneifolia</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1213,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,1249,1274]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Life history.</emphasis>
Known only from the bud galls of the asexual generation, which are spherical, single-chambered, 
<quantity box="[151,277,1286,1310]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" metricValueMax="1.4" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" unit="mm" value="12.0" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="10.0">10–14 mm</quantity>
in diameter, with velvety, sometimes slightly wrinkled surface, broadly attached to the branch or sometimes to the trunk (
<figureCitation box="[437,524,1321,1346]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="37.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Galls on Quercus boissieri and Q. ithaburensis. 35. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum, asexual generation on Quercus boissieri; 36. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum (A) and Neuroterus numismalis (B), asexual generations on Q. boissieri; 37. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis; 38. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis, gall dissected to show inner chamber; 39. Aphelonyx persica gall ivaded by the inquiline Synergus variabilis on Quercus ithaburensis; 40. Same, old gall with emergence holes of inquilines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610035/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
), often in clusters of 5–8. The gall contains an internal ovoid chamber that is attached to the inside wall in young galls but detaches from it and rolls freely inside the mature gall (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1423,1357,1382]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="37.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Galls on Quercus boissieri and Q. ithaburensis. 35. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum, asexual generation on Quercus boissieri; 36. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum (A) and Neuroterus numismalis (B), asexual generations on Q. boissieri; 37. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis; 38. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis, gall dissected to show inner chamber; 39. Aphelonyx persica gall ivaded by the inquiline Synergus variabilis on Quercus ithaburensis; 40. Same, old gall with emergence holes of inquilines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610035/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
). Young galls are light green, turning brown when mature. Old galls remain on the trees for several years.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="470" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1213,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,1429,1454]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Phenology.</emphasis>
Galls appear in August and adults emerge from them in October-November. In the present study one adult emerged from a gall on 
<taxonomicName box="[529,628,1465,1489]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="libani">
<emphasis box="[529,628,1465,1489]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Q. libani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in January.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="470" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1213,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1501,1526]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,425,1501,1526]" name="Israel" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Israel</collectingCountry>
: Common on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sternlicht" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[582,754,1501,1525]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ithaburensis">
<emphasis box="[582,754,1501,1525]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Q. ithaburensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
throughout its distribution range; on 
<taxonomicName box="[1172,1271,1501,1525]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="libani">
<emphasis box="[1172,1271,1501,1525]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Q. libani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
found only on Mt. Hermon at 
<quantity box="[324,416,1537,1562]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.78" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" unit="m" value="1780.0">1780 m</quantity>
.a.s.l. Elsewhere: 
<collectingCountry box="[606,687,1537,1562]" name="Turkey" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Turkey</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[698,760,1537,1562]" name="Syria" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Syria</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[771,872,1537,1562]" name="Lebanon" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Lebanon</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[883,932,1538,1561]" name="Iran" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Iran</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="470" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,1213,1814]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1573,1598]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Comments.</emphasis>
Galls of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melika, Stone, Sadeghi &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2004" box="[440,554,1574,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Aphelonyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[440,554,1574,1597]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">A. persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Giraud" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[874,1008,1573,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Aphelonyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerricola">
<emphasis box="[874,1008,1573,1597]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">A. cerricola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1239,1573,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Aphelonyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kordestanica">
<emphasis box="[1063,1239,1573,1597]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">A. kordestanica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but these species have not been found in 
<collectingCountry box="[416,482,1609,1634]" name="Israel" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Israel</collectingCountry>
. The galls are often invaded by the inquiline 
<taxonomicName authority="Mayr" authorityName="Mayr" box="[991,1277,1609,1634]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Synergus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis box="[991,1207,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Synergus variabilis</emphasis>
Mayr
</taxonomicName>
, especially on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Sternlicht" baseAuthorityYear="1968" box="[151,327,1645,1669]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ithaburensis">
<emphasis box="[151,327,1645,1669]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Q. ithaburensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. An invaded gall is bigger, irregularly shaped and multichambered (
<figureCitation box="[1145,1281,1645,1670]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="37.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Galls on Quercus boissieri and Q. ithaburensis. 35. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum, asexual generation on Quercus boissieri; 36. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum (A) and Neuroterus numismalis (B), asexual generations on Q. boissieri; 37. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis; 38. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis, gall dissected to show inner chamber; 39. Aphelonyx persica gall ivaded by the inquiline Synergus variabilis on Quercus ithaburensis; 40. Same, old gall with emergence holes of inquilines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610035/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Figs 39–40</figureCitation>
), whereas an uninvaded gall is spherical and single-chambered (
<figureCitation box="[722,854,1681,1706]" captionStart="FIGURES 35–40" captionStartId="37.[151,264,1682,1705]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[150,1424,193,1646]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURES 35–40. Galls on Quercus boissieri and Q. ithaburensis. 35. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum, asexual generation on Quercus boissieri; 36. Neuroterus quercsbaccarum (A) and Neuroterus numismalis (B), asexual generations on Q. boissieri; 37. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis; 38. Aphelonyx persica, asexual generation on Quercus ithaburensis, gall dissected to show inner chamber; 39. Aphelonyx persica gall ivaded by the inquiline Synergus variabilis on Quercus ithaburensis; 40. Same, old gall with emergence holes of inquilines." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610035/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Figs 37–38</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Sternlicht, M." box="[873,1078,1681,1706]" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" pagination="17 - 57" refId="ref36265" refString="Sternlicht, M. (1968 b) The oak galls of Israel (Quercus calliprinos Webb, and Quercus ithaburensis Decne.). Israel Journal of Entomology, 3, 17 - 57." type="journal article" year="1968">Sternlicht (1968b)</bibRefCitation>
listed the axesual generation of 
<taxonomicName authority="Hartig" authorityName="Hartig" box="[151,422,1717,1742]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Andricus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kollari">
<emphasis box="[151,339,1717,1741]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Andricus kollari</emphasis>
Hartig
</taxonomicName>
as occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[621,683,1717,1742]" name="Israel" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Israel</collectingCountry>
(his 
<figureCitation box="[749,881,1717,1742]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–22" captionStartId="34.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1641]" captionTargetId="figure@34.[152,1435,193,1644]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURES 17–22. Galls on Quercus boissieri. 17. Andricus coriariformis, asexual generation; 18. Andricus moreae, asexual generation; 19. Andricus sp. 1, asexual generation; 20. Andricus sternlichti, asexual generation; 21. Andricus megatruncicolus, asexual generation; 22. Biorhiza pallida, sexual generation." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2610029/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Figs 18–20</figureCitation>
) but we never found this species in 
<collectingCountry box="[1322,1384,1717,1742]" name="Israel" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Israel</collectingCountry>
and conclude that Sternlicht mistook its galls for those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melika, Stone, Sadeghi &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2004" box="[768,978,1753,1777]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Aphelonyx" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="persica">
<emphasis box="[768,978,1753,1777]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Aphelonyx persica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Galls of the two species are somewhat similar in shape and colour but those of 
<taxonomicName box="[600,706,1789,1813]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Andricus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kollari">
<emphasis box="[600,706,1789,1813]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">A. kollari</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
develop only on oaks from section 
<taxonomicName box="[1107,1201,1790,1813]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="470" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1107,1201,1790,1813]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="470">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
